== a space in the match quotes it:
'spacey file.txt'
== a plain match stays unquoted:
plainfile.txt
== a dollar in the match quotes it:
'dollar$x.txt'
== inside a single quote the space match completes bare within it:
spacey file.txt
== inside a double quote the space match completes bare within it:
spacey file.txt
== a closed quoted directory continues through an unquoted slash:
'PATH'/'space file.txt'
'PATH'/plain.txt
'PATH'/star-one.txt
'PATH'/tool
== a partial basename follows a closed quoted directory:
'PATH'/plain.txt
== a quoted directory that contains a space keeps its spelling:
'space dir'/mixed.txt
== adjacent quoted and unquoted directory bytes are decoded together:
P'A'TH/plain.txt
== an escaped directory keeps its spelling:
space\ dir/mixed.txt
== a double-quoted variable directory remains active:
"$HOME"/home.txt
== a single-quoted variable directory remains literal:
'$HOME'/literal-variable.txt
== an open single-quoted variable directory remains literal:
$HOME/literal-variable.txt
== an open double-quoted variable directory remains active:
$HOME/home.txt
== an active tilde directory expands:
~/home.txt
== a quoted tilde directory remains literal:
'~'/literal-tilde.txt
== a quoted glob remains literal:
== an unquoted glob after a quoted directory expands:
'PATH'/plain.txt 'PATH'/'space file.txt' 'PATH'/star-one.txt
== command position keeps only runnable files:
'PATH'/tool
